00:15:45,400 --> 00:15:50,720
they begin advocating immediately, meaning, "We 
should do this." Or, "No, we should not do this." 

187
00:15:51,840 --> 00:15:57,960
Me, I always took the opposite approach, and I 
still do. I inquire first. I dial up inquiry,  

188
00:15:57,960 --> 00:16:03,760
I tone down my advocacy, meaning I am going 
to respect the other opinion. I'm going to  

189
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:07,200
ask a ton of questions because I fundamentally 
believe maybe there's something I don't know and  

190
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:12,440
there's information that I need to understand 
to make a better decision. In the beginning,  

191
00:16:12,440 --> 00:16:17,520
dial up inquiry. And then once the person 
that you're talking to feels heard and  

192
00:16:17,520 --> 00:16:20,680
you actually have absorbed information, 
and maybe you changed your mind, maybe  

193
00:16:20,680 --> 00:16:26,800
not though, that's when you begin to advocate.
Oftentimes you just come into these conversations  

194
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:30,280
where everyone just advocates, advocate, advocate, 
advocate, and you're talking past each other.  

195
00:16:30,280 --> 00:16:38,480
You're not even reflecting on what the other 
person is saying. Sometimes when I talk too much,  

196
00:16:38,480 --> 00:16:46,520
I tell myself, "Wait, inquire. Dial down advocacy. 
Just take a breath, take a moment, take a beat,  

197
00:16:46,520 --> 00:16:51,080
and actually ask some questions and see 
why the other person feels so strongly."

198
00:16:51,080 --> 00:16:55,920
I think that's such a good specific thing 
you can do because I think a lot of people  

199
00:16:55,920 --> 00:16:58,960
want to do what you're doing. They're like, 
"Okay, I'm going to listen. I'm going to ask  

200
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:02,040
questions." But then they get a reaction. 
Someone's like, "Hey, we need to change  

201
00:17:02,040 --> 00:17:05,640
this thing on the landing page." And you're like, 
"No, that's a terrible idea." Or, "That's going  

202
00:17:05,640 --> 00:17:09,560
to take all this time. It's going to throw off a 
roadmap." And there's this bodily, "Oh, no, I need  

203
00:17:09,560 --> 00:17:16,000
to stop this thingy." And so your advice here is 
pay attention to, am I talking too long? I guess,  

204
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:20,160
is that the advice? Am I talking too long? Am I 
saying too much? And start just inquiring instead.

205
00:17:20,160 --> 00:17:20,600
Yeah.

206
00:17:20,600 --> 00:17:21,000
Awesome.

207
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:26,080
Totally. And lead with questions. Basically, 
approach every conversation with curiosity.  

208
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:31,000
Don't come in, because people usually when 
they prepare for a meeting, I've seen many  

209
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:35,880
PMs do this, and you prepare with, "Here is my 
view, and here are the bullets that support my  

210
00:17:35,880 --> 00:17:39,760
view." And that's the wrong way to approach it. 
I think when you want to go into a conversation,  

211
00:17:40,440 --> 00:17:45,880
you start the conversation with questions. Prepare 
the questions that come from a place of curiosity  

212
00:17:45,880 --> 00:17:50,080
of the things that you want to know more about 
and you want to learn from the other perspective,  

213
00:17:50,080 --> 00:17:54,960
and then check yourself to see if you still want 
to advocate for the same point of view or not.

214
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:58,840
We had an awesome episode with Ami Vora. 
She's CPO at Faire, and she is also extremely  

215
00:17:59,520 --> 00:18:04,120
good at this and a huge advocate of starting with 
questions and understanding what she's missing.

216
00:18:04,120 --> 00:18:08,160
Totally. Well, the other thing I would say 
is, the other motto that has really helped  

217
00:18:08,160 --> 00:18:17,000
me drive impact, and I use the analogy 
of the bear, and I've always told myself,  

218
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:26,040
"Don't be afraid to poke the bear." And what that 
means is don't self-censor. If you have a strong  

219
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:30,960
view after you've really grounded yourself in the 
truth and you feel like you've done your homework  

220
00:18:30,960 --> 00:18:37,560
and you've asked all the questions, if you still 
disagree, if you still feel like we're going in  

221
00:18:37,560 --> 00:18:42,840
the wrong direction, don't be afraid to poke 
the bear no matter how hard things get. It's  

222
00:18:42,840 --> 00:18:47,920
interesting because I think a lot of, especially 
as an organization matures, you find yourself in  

223
00:18:47,920 --> 00:18:56,320
meetings with many execs, founders, et cetera, 
it's often hard to voice your real opinion.  

224
00:18:56,320 --> 00:19:01,800
And you usually tone it down a little bit because 
you're afraid of being the only one who disagrees,  

225
00:19:01,800 --> 00:19:07,200
or sounding stupid or things like that.
And so I remember it was probably 2014 or  

226
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:13,800
2013 where I made a promise to myself, "I'm going 
to always poke the bear no matter how hard things  

227
00:19:13,800 --> 00:19:17,200
get." Because at the end of the day, what's the 
worst thing that's going to happen? Did I get  

228
00:19:17,200 --> 00:19:23,440
fired? Why would I even be afraid of that? But 
if I do, I'll find another gig. Life is short.  

229
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:28,840
You've done this really well, where I feel like 
you've also always... I remember when we were  

230
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:31,560
working on Instant Book, you've definitely 
poked the bear, where you were like, "You guys  

231
00:19:31,560 --> 00:19:35,600
are wrong. This is how we have to approach 
it." And I've always really appreciated it.

232
00:19:35,600 --> 00:19:40,200
Thanks, man. Is there an example of maybe working 
with Brian where you poked Brian and like, "No?"

233
00:19:40,200 --> 00:19:42,960
Yeah, absolutely. I've poked the 
bear many times. And by the way,  

234
00:19:42,960 --> 00:19:47,960
I've been humbled many times. It's not like I 
poked the bear and I rightfully poked the bear.  

235
00:19:47,960 --> 00:19:54,360
Sometimes I learn stuff and I realize I was wrong.
A couple of examples that come to mind. One,  

236
00:19:54,360 --> 00:20:01,160
I remember having these debates with 
all basically senior leaders at Airbnb,  

237
00:20:01,160 --> 00:20:08,400
just about every couple of years actually, around 
how much supply should we have on the platform and  

238
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:13,320
what kind of supply should be on the platform. And 
there was one school of thought where we needed  

239
00:20:13,320 --> 00:20:18,400
basically... That school of thought represented 
the view that we needed all supply out there  

240
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:25,320
to be on our platform, regardless of if it was a 
person hosting, it was a vacation rental, it was a  

241
00:20:25,320 --> 00:20:31,360
hotel. We just needed all supply on the platform.
I came at it from a very different perspective  

242
00:20:31,360 --> 00:20:35,080
where I felt like that wasn't actually our 
mission from the very beginning. And although  

243
00:20:35,080 --> 00:20:40,320
I understood that in the short term, the numbers 
probably would go up and you would choose growth,  

244
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:46,000
but at the same time that wouldn't in the long 
run be a point of differentiation for us. And  

245
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:53,200
so I had a very different point of view, and it 
was very hard in that conversation. Everyone's  

246
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:58,720
excited. Everyone seems to be aligning around 
the point of view to be the voice that's poking.  

247
00:20:58,720 --> 00:21:05,720
And this is like, "Nope, let me share why I think 
maybe we should go in a different direction." And  

248
00:21:05,720 --> 00:21:14,840
it's when I remember telling myself that I am 
here to surface and share information that will  

249
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:19,760
help the group make a decision, that's what gave 
me peace of mind to actually poke the bear and be  

250
00:21:19,760 --> 00:21:26,840
able to surface the things that I've seen.
The other thing is when we were working on  

251
00:21:26,840 --> 00:21:32,720
the Instant Book, change from Request to Book 
to Instant Book for the entire marketplace,  

252
00:21:32,720 --> 00:21:37,440
that was very challenging. And I remember 
getting up on stage in front of the entire  

253
00:21:37,440 --> 00:21:43,960
company and explaining why this is 
actually good for humanity. Literally,  

254
00:21:43,960 --> 00:21:53,160
those words. Many people disagreed, and it was 
not an easy thing to do, but had to be done.

255
00:21:53,160 --> 00:21:56,920
And one thread that I've noticed across all 
these things, and noticed working with you,  

256
00:21:56,920 --> 00:22:00,520
is it's not like just making a case 
for something you could disagree  

257
00:22:00,520 --> 00:22:04,160
with. It's showing the data that 
will convince them they are wrong,  

258
00:22:04,160 --> 00:22:10,720
or here's what they're missing. It's not like a 
speech. It's, "Here's the data," and asking them,  

259
00:22:10,720 --> 00:22:13,760
"What data would you want to see to 
convince you this might be not as you-"

260
00:22:13,760 --> 00:22:20,560
Totally. I think I remember doing a Q&A with the 
whole company on the Instant Book topic. This was  

261
00:22:20,560 --> 00:22:27,000
a very long time ago, but I still remember where 
instead of, again, advocating for a point of view,  

262
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,080
I just asked all the people that were 
concerned what their main questions were,  

263
00:22:30,080 --> 00:22:35,800
and then we just tackled them one by one and 
we would talk. There's just something very  

264
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:41,880
disarming when you embrace the questions, 
you embrace the negativity, and you have an  

265
00:22:41,880 --> 00:22:46,240
open mind that maybe there's some things that you 
missed and some things that you didn't consider.

266
00:22:46,240 --> 00:22:50,840
I love that. Okay, there's so many little nuggets 
already through this that I just want to come back  

267
00:22:50,840 --> 00:22:57,360
to and make sure people take away of how to be 
more successful. And this is not just as a product  

268
00:22:57,360 --> 00:23:03,440
leader, this just as a leader in any company. The 
first is advice around thinking about impact above  

269
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:08,640
all else. And the very simple heuristic that I 
wrote down as you were talking is ask yourself,  

270
00:23:08,640 --> 00:23:15,080
"What are the priorities for the company? How 
can I impact these priorities?" And to do that,  

271
00:23:15,080 --> 00:23:20,800
think about the levers that drive the business. 
And where do I think I can make an impact to drive  

272
00:23:20,800 --> 00:23:26,520
these priorities and drive the business?
Two is inquiry first. When you disagree  

273
00:23:26,520 --> 00:23:32,080
with something or when you want to say no, 
start with understanding, asking questions,  

274
00:23:32,080 --> 00:23:37,480
dialing up inquiry versus advocacy, versus, 
"Here's what I think." Poking the bear,  

275
00:23:37,480 --> 00:23:42,760
which is really fun, just this idea of don't be 
afraid to disagree with someone in power. And your  

276
00:23:42,760 --> 00:23:47,680
advice here is disagree with, "Here's data you 
may be aware of here. Have you seen this? Hey,  

277
00:23:47,680 --> 00:23:50,240
check this out." Or, "What is it that 
would convince you you're wrong?" 

278
00:23:51,480 --> 00:23:54,720
And then is there anything else I 
missed? Otherwise, we'll go on to more.

279
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:55,360
I think that was great.

280
00:23:55,360 --> 00:23:55,680
Okay, cool.

281
00:23:55,680 --> 00:23:58,440
Don't poke the bear for the sake of poking.  

282
00:23:59,560 --> 00:24:02,640
Share the information that you think 
will be helpful to make a decision.

283
00:24:02,640 --> 00:24:08,720
Cool. Anything else? Any other things you've found 
to be really effective in helping you succeed?

284
00:24:08,720 --> 00:24:15,120
Oftentimes it's about also being able 
to be impactful at a company that is in  

285
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:20,000
hyperscale and is growing quickly. A lot of 
it is actually just psychological. It's not  

286
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:25,160
like there are these core skills. Sure, 
you got to have some baseline skills,  

287
00:24:25,680 --> 00:24:33,960
but a lot of it is day-to-day regulating your 
mind. And it's so easy to get lost in the sea  

288
00:24:33,960 --> 00:24:39,120
of projects, the sea of priorities, the 
sea of opinions and, like I said before,  

289
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:45,160
dwell on the dependencies that exist between 
teams without actually asking yourself what  

290
00:24:45,160 --> 00:24:52,280
you can do in the moment to make an impact.
And for me, I've actually used two tools,  

291
00:24:52,280 --> 00:24:56,360
which, some of them you may remember, 
that have helped me. The first tool,  

292
00:24:56,920 --> 00:25:03,974
this is again purely psychological, to 
help my mind, it's the serenity prayer. I-

293
00:25:03,974 --> 00:25:08,280
It's the Serenity Prayer. So the Serenity Prayer 
goes something like this. "Grant me the serenity  

294
00:25:08,280 --> 00:25:14,560
to accept the things that I cannot change, the 
courage to change the things that I can, and the  

295
00:25:14,560 --> 00:25:23,960
wisdom to know the difference." That prayer was so 
powerful for me that I actually wrote it out on a  

296
00:25:23,960 --> 00:25:31,040
piece of paper, like on post-it notes, and I would 
read that thing every other day. And it would help  

297
00:25:31,040 --> 00:25:37,440
me just take a step back from the day to day and 
just put into context what's actually important,  

298
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:42,040
and again, what is in my control today 
and the things that I can actually do?

299
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:42,200
Wow.

300
00:25:42,200 --> 00:25:44,440
So that, highly recommend.

301
00:25:44,440 --> 00:25:45,680
Did none of that.

302
00:25:45,680 --> 00:25:49,000
The other one, which you may 
remember, is the shit bucket.

303
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:50,520
I do remember that.

304
00:25:50,520 --> 00:25:56,840
So the shit bucket was a visual analogy 
where I would take a piece of paper,  

305
00:25:56,840 --> 00:26:01,000
and some of it actually wasn't as visual, 
it was real, I would take a piece of paper,  

306
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:08,200
I would write down something that wasn't going 
well, perhaps a dependency, perhaps a project,  

307
00:26:08,200 --> 00:26:10,960
perhaps a meeting that I was going to have 
that I knew I was going to be frustrated,  

308
00:26:10,960 --> 00:26:15,120
or maybe we didn't even decide to go the 
way that I deeply felt passionate about. I  

309
00:26:15,120 --> 00:26:20,800
would write it down, I would crumble a piece of 
paper, and I would throw it in my shit bucket,  

310
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:24,960
basically. And the rule was once I threw 
something in the shit bucket, I couldn't take  

311
00:26:24,960 --> 00:26:32,400
anything out of the bucket, so I would not dwell 
on the things that I just needed to let go of. 

312
00:26:33,400 --> 00:26:40,000
So this was a very powerful tool that, like I'm 
a perfectionist, I just deeply care about many  

313
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:46,280
different things, and I have a hard time letting 
go. And so for me, it was just a reminder that  

314
00:26:46,280 --> 00:26:53,080
I need to let some things go and focus on the 
things that matter. And I actually, I remember  

315
00:26:53,080 --> 00:27:01,360
even going into one of the ones with my direct 
where I would sometimes lead. I could tell the PM  

316
00:27:01,360 --> 00:27:06,200
is a bit frustrated about how things are going, 
and one of my first questions would be, "What  

317
00:27:06,200 --> 00:27:13,680
are we throwing in the shit bucket today?" It's 
actually a very liberating thing that you can do.

318
00:27:13,680 --> 00:27:17,840
And did you have a special trash that was your 
shit bucket, or is it the regular trash can?

319
00:27:17,840 --> 00:27:21,280
Every meeting room always had a trash 
can, and I would always throw stuff  

320
00:27:21,280 --> 00:27:23,720
into the trash can whenever 
I got upset about something.

321
00:27:23,720 --> 00:27:26,820
It's like a different 
dimension trash can or bucket.

322
00:27:26,820 --> 00:27:27,080
Yeah.

323
00:27:27,080 --> 00:27:29,120
Is there something you remember 
throwing in that shit bucket that  

324
00:27:29,120 --> 00:27:31,720
would be an interesting example or story to share?

325
00:27:31,720 --> 00:27:35,640
I remember there was one person 
who I deeply wanted to hire,  

326
00:27:35,640 --> 00:27:40,920
who I felt was just phenomenal and would 
be such an amazing addition to the team,  

327
00:27:40,920 --> 00:27:45,280
and I tried and tried and tried for a very 
long time, and I just failed. I just could  

328
00:27:45,280 --> 00:27:53,880
not get that person to join. And at some point, 
it became counterproductive and I had to let go,  

329
00:27:53,880 --> 00:27:58,800
and literally just wrote like, "Okay, getting 
this person into the company," I'm like,  

330
00:27:58,800 --> 00:28:03,680
"this is not going to happen. I've got to 
move on at this point." Just threw it in.

331
00:28:03,680 --> 00:28:05,480
I love these two pieces of advice and it touches  

332
00:28:05,480 --> 00:28:11,880
on how mentally challenging it is to 
be a leader at a hyper-growth company.

333
00:28:11,880 --> 00:28:12,920
Yeah.

334
00:28:12,920 --> 00:28:17,000
Is there anything you can share there about just 
that part of the world? People see your career  

335
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:21,840
like, "Holy shit, look at him. He's running 
Airbnb's business. What an amazing life."  

336
00:28:21,840 --> 00:28:25,400
There's a lot of pain behind it. Is there anything 
there that would be useful to people, you think?

337
00:28:25,400 --> 00:28:32,280
There's a lot there. It's not like it was smooth 
sailing for me every single year. I had plenty  

338
00:28:32,280 --> 00:28:40,560
of challenges just personally going through that 
journey. You take a job and then you're sometimes  

339
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:45,800
just not prepared where it's going to take you. 
And the reality is, every three to six months my  

340
00:28:45,800 --> 00:28:51,040
job changed, so I would just get comfortable 
in the role I was in, let's say in the very  

341
00:28:51,040 --> 00:28:57,320
early days, I was literally an IC growth PM with a 
tiny team, got pretty comfortable, and then a year  

342
00:28:57,320 --> 00:29:02,640
later everything changed, and I was suddenly 
leading a team of 20. Then a few years later,  

343
00:29:02,640 --> 00:29:07,080
things changed again. I was leading a team of a 
couple hundred. Then a few years later, again,  

344
00:29:07,080 --> 00:29:13,520
everything changed. And you just, everything 
that you take comfort in, in your current role,  

345
00:29:13,520 --> 00:29:19,160
breaks. The process breaks, how you hire breaks, 
how you spend your time breaks, the projects you  

346
00:29:19,160 --> 00:29:25,360
work on, everything breaks, and you've got to 
reinvent yourself, and that is very hard to do. 

347
00:29:25,360 --> 00:29:32,600
So one thing that I've learned is you've got to 
ask for help. It takes a village, right? You can't  

348
00:29:32,600 --> 00:29:38,080
just get there by yourself. And that's actually 
something that Brian taught me, where, I mean,  

349
00:29:38,080 --> 00:29:45,760
this guy just grew. Every six months, it was like 
a different person, and a lot of his secret sauce  

350
00:29:45,760 --> 00:29:51,560
is not being afraid to ask people for help who are 
experts in the thing that you're trying to learn.  

351
00:29:51,560 --> 00:29:55,640
I mean, my motto is, "Ask for the impossible, 
and sometimes you're going to be surprised."  

352
00:29:56,400 --> 00:30:01,480
There are people out there that are experts 
in something who actually want to help you.

353
00:30:02,560 --> 00:30:08,960
That's awesome advice. Also the Serenity Prayer, 
so powerful. I did not know that about you. I want  

354
00:30:08,960 --> 00:30:12,760
to spend time talking about things you've 
learned about scaling Airbnb and the org,  

355
00:30:12,760 --> 00:30:17,120
but before we get to that, is there anything 
else that you think contributed to your  

356
00:30:17,120 --> 00:30:22,600
success individually as a leader, 
any other behaviors or mindsets?

357
00:30:22,600 --> 00:30:35,560
I mean, I think it's building teams and realizing 
that sometimes, when you build a team, and this is  

358
00:30:35,560 --> 00:30:41,160
actually often misunderstood, I think when people 
build teams, they try to make sure every person  

359
00:30:41,160 --> 00:30:46,760
on the team is good at just about everything. You 
typically go through the process of here are my  

360
00:30:46,760 --> 00:30:56,000
strengths, here are my development areas. And 
typically the development areas are you try to  

361
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:02,000
develop just about single thing so that you can be 
good at almost every single skill that exists, and  

362
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:07,040
I just think that's the wrong mindset. Instead, 
what I've learned over time, is instead of trying  

363
00:31:07,040 --> 00:31:13,560
to find people that are good at everything, you 
need to look for people who spike on specific  

364
00:31:13,560 --> 00:31:21,320
things and then add them to a team with different 
spikes. So there's no single person that spikes  

365
00:31:21,320 --> 00:31:25,600
on absolutely everything, that's very rare, but 
they spike on something that's very crucial to the  

366
00:31:25,600 --> 00:31:31,320
team. And if you assemble different spikes on a 
given team, that team is going to do great things,  

367
00:31:31,320 --> 00:31:37,840
as long as everybody inquires and everybody 
starts asking questions, actually listens to  

368
00:31:37,840 --> 00:31:44,040
other people, versus just coming about that.
So even now, as an investor, when I look or  

369
00:31:44,040 --> 00:31:50,200
when I talk to founders, the first question in 
my head is like, what does this founder spike on,  

370
00:31:50,200 --> 00:31:56,440
and how is that spike relevant to the problem that 
they're tackling today, and how well does this  

371
00:31:56,440 --> 00:32:02,600
founder hire to bring other spikes to the team? 
