00:48:43,280 --> 00:48:47,560
And I remember asking him, "What do you mean?" I 
was like, "Our numbers are up and to the right,  

554
00:48:48,120 --> 00:48:52,800
we're chipping quickly, everything's great. 
What do you mean? What are you unhappy with?"  

555
00:48:52,800 --> 00:49:02,040
And his response was, "Things are just too calm. I 
don't like it." And I was like, "Okay, what do you  

556
00:49:02,040 --> 00:49:12,040
mean? Calm is great," like I operate in calm. 
And he then picked a project that he thought  

557
00:49:12,040 --> 00:49:16,280
was important - I think it was actually host 
onboarding at the time - and of course, on this  

558
00:49:16,280 --> 00:49:22,400
project, I remember we had this perfectly crafted 
timeline. We're going to design this for the next  

559
00:49:22,400 --> 00:49:28,120
four weeks and then we're going to start building, 
and we're going to deploy in certain pockets of  

560
00:49:28,120 --> 00:49:32,480
users, we're going to learn, we're going to 
iterate, et cetera, very rational timeline. 

561
00:49:33,640 --> 00:49:38,360
And he said, "Yeah, I don't care about any of 
that. We're going to design this in 24 hours."  

562
00:49:38,360 --> 00:49:47,160
And I was just like mind blown own, right, like, 
one, how? Two, the ripples that's going to send  

563
00:49:47,160 --> 00:49:51,600
through the organization, because I knew all 
the people that were involved on building this,  

564
00:49:51,600 --> 00:49:58,280
and we had this whole neat flow. And we did design 
it, actually, in 24 hours, well, it took a little  

565
00:49:58,280 --> 00:50:00,040
bit longer, but we designed it very quickly, 
and what I learned in that moment is that ...

566
00:50:00,040 --> 00:50:06,880
Very quickly, and what I learned in that moment 
is, that was actually an example of chaos that he  

567
00:50:06,880 --> 00:50:14,000
inserted into this very calm building process, 
and that chaos forced us, with our artificial  

568
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:22,920
time constraint, to dial up our intuition and to 
think a bit more creatively than maybe we would  

569
00:50:22,920 --> 00:50:28,160
have in the past. Now, that didn't always work, 
because there were examples of this where you're  

570
00:50:28,160 --> 00:50:32,480
just like, "I don't know what the answer is. I 
need more time to design this, and to think about  

571
00:50:32,480 --> 00:50:36,440
this problem." There were definitely examples 
of that, but there were many examples where it  

572
00:50:36,440 --> 00:50:43,360
