go with your gut and actually innovate.

573
00:50:43,360 --> 00:50:45,560
That's an amazing story, and it 
reminds me of something else,  

574
00:50:45,560 --> 00:50:51,120
just to take a quick tangent here. Brian 
is incredible at just asking people always,  

575
00:50:51,120 --> 00:50:54,280
"That's a great goal you have there. 
What would it take to 10x that goal?" 

576
00:50:54,280 --> 00:51:00,120
He'd get to the FP&A projections, and he's like, 
"Great. How do we 10x this?" I found that to be  

577
00:51:00,120 --> 00:51:03,720
really scary, but also, really effective in 
helping people think a lot bigger. Is there  

578
00:51:03,720 --> 00:51:07,920
something there you can share about just what 
you learned from Brian about thinking that big?

579
00:51:07,920 --> 00:51:13,640
I think it's less about hitting the goal. I think 
a lot of people, when they see really big goals,  

580
00:51:13,640 --> 00:51:18,480
they get immediately afraid of the 
goals, because they think, "Oh my God,  

581
00:51:18,480 --> 00:51:22,240
I don't know how to hit this. If we don't hit 
it, what happens?" You start thinking about all  

582
00:51:22,240 --> 00:51:29,160
the downstream consequences. The reality is, it's 
not about hitting the goal, it's about thinking  

583
00:51:29,160 --> 00:51:34,960
how to hit the goal, and going through that 
creative journey of, what does the world need  

584
00:51:34,960 --> 00:51:39,880
to look like for this to be true, this crazy 
goal to be true? How should we think about it? 

585
00:51:39,880 --> 00:51:47,200
Oftentimes, it pushes you to test extremes, when 
the whole world is going to operate this way,  

586
00:51:47,200 --> 00:51:52,000
or nobody in the world is going to operate 
this way versus something in between. Usually,  

587
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:55,040
it's when you start testing the 
extremes that you begin to realize,  

588
00:51:57,720 --> 00:52:00,600
"This is the path that we should actually take."

589
00:52:00,600 --> 00:52:05,160
Yeah, I've found exactly the same thing, just 
thinking backwards from what is the best possible  

590
00:52:05,160 --> 00:52:10,520
thing we could do, versus incrementally forward 
