00:55:30,520 --> 00:55:34,960
as the company is growing and org 
is scaling about org design hiring?

634
00:55:34,960 --> 00:55:41,360
So for me, one of the hardest things 
about building teams and going through  

635
00:55:41,360 --> 00:55:47,360
hyper growth was the fact that you're going 
to lose a lot of friends on that journey. You  

636
00:55:47,360 --> 00:55:52,240
just have to be prepared to say goodbye 
to your friend. Meaning when you start,  

637
00:55:52,240 --> 00:55:57,560
you build really deep relationships with people.
When you're a smaller startup, you typically have  

638
00:55:57,560 --> 00:56:03,080
one-on-one interaction and you know everybody 
and you have that connection with people. And  

639
00:56:03,080 --> 00:56:08,760
the reality is, if the company is 
truly going through hyper growth,  

640
00:56:08,760 --> 00:56:15,480
most people are not going to scale. It is very 
rare for somebody to scale with the company. 

641
00:56:15,480 --> 00:56:19,000
I mean, we actually, so at Index, we 
wrote a book, Scaling Through Chaos,  

642
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:28,120
and there was this crazy stat where basically when 
you look at many, many companies that reached a  

643
00:56:28,120 --> 00:56:34,120
thousand people and were successful, when you look 
back to the first 10 employees, you realize that  

644
00:56:34,120 --> 00:56:39,320
only two to three of those ten first employees 
stayed with the company when the company reached  

645
00:56:39,320 --> 00:56:48,160
a thousand people. And that's just so indicative 
of what will actually happen in practice. 

646
00:56:48,160 --> 00:56:56,480
There are certain skills that you have that are 
good for in the specific domain for a period of  

647
00:56:56,480 --> 00:57:05,720
time and that time is not universal forever. 
At some point, everybody taps out and so just  

648
00:57:05,720 --> 00:57:12,520
having that realization is, it's tough. It's 
tough emotionally. It was one of the hardest  

649
00:57:12,520 --> 00:57:21,400
things for me as a leader, and I would say the 
way to break out of that is to ask for help and  

650
00:57:21,400 --> 00:57:29,160
to try to learn as much as you can about what 
the next role for you is going to look like. So,  

651
00:57:29,160 --> 00:57:34,960
that's one thing that I've learned.
I would say another thing is that all  

652
00:57:34,960 --> 00:57:42,640
org charts suck. There is no good org chart. 
Every single org chart has problems. So you  

653
00:57:42,640 --> 00:57:46,480
can be organized around business units, you 
can be functionally organized, you can be  

654
00:57:46,480 --> 00:57:52,240
organized around problems, and the reality is 
every single one of those constructs sucks. 

655
00:57:52,240 --> 00:57:58,800
There are pros and cons to each approach. If 
you organize yourself into business units,  

656
00:57:58,800 --> 00:58:03,120
the problem you typically run into is silos. 
When people start basically advocating for  

657
00:58:03,120 --> 00:58:09,840
